Alright, I'm going to guide you through building a simple console-based trivia quiz game using C#. This game will ask users multiple-choice questions, accept their answers, and keep track of their scores. By the end, you'll have a fun little program to test your knowledge or even entertain your friends.

### Step 1: Setting Up the Project

First, make sure you have Visual Studio or Visual Studio Code installed on your machine with the C# extension. Create a new console application project.

- Open Visual Studio.
- Go to `File` > `New` > `Project`.
- Select `Console App` and name your project (e.g., `TriviaQuiz`).
- Click `Create`.

### Step 2: Designing the Game Structure

We need to plan out how our game will work. Here’s a basic structure:

1. **Question Class**: To hold the question, options, and the correct answer.
2. **Quiz Class**: To manage the list of questions, track the score, and handle user interactions.
3. **Program Class**: To run the game.

### Step 3: Creating the Question Class

This class will represent each question in our quiz.

```csharp
public class Question
{
    public string Text { get; set; }
    public string[] Options { get; set; }
    public char CorrectAnswer { get; set; }

    public Question(string text, string[] options, char correctAnswer)
    {
        Text = text;
        Options = options;
        CorrectAnswer = correctAnswer;
    }
}
```

### Step 4: Creating the Quiz Class

This class will handle the quiz logic.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class Quiz
{
    private List<Question> questions;
    private int score;

    public Quiz(List<Question> questions)
    {
        this.questions = questions;
        this.score = 0;
    }

    public void Run()
    {
        foreach (var question in questions)
        {
            DisplayQuestion(question);
            char userAnswer = GetUserAnswer();
            if (userAnswer == question.CorrectAnswer)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Correct!");
                score++;
            }
            else
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Wrong! The correct answer is {question.CorrectAnswer}");
            }
            Console.WriteLine();
        }
        DisplayScore();
    }

    private void DisplayQuestion(Question question)
    {
        Console.WriteLine(question.Text);
        for (int i = 0; i < question.Options.Length; i++)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"({(char)('A' + i)}) {question.Options[i]}");
        }
    }

    private char GetUserAnswer()
    {
        Console.Write("Your answer: ");
        string input = Console.ReadLine().Trim().ToUpper();
        if (input.Length == 1 && input >= "A" && input <= "D")
        {
            return input[0];
        }
        else
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Invalid input. Please enter A, B, C, or D.");
            return GetUserAnswer(); // Recursively ask again
        }
    }

    private void DisplayScore()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Quiz completed! Your score is {score}/{questions.Count}");
    }
}
```

### Step 5: Setting Up the Program Class

This is where the application starts.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        List<Question> questions = new List<Question>
        {
            new Question("What is the capital of France?", 
                new string[] { "Paris", "London", "Berlin", "Madrid" }, 'A'),
            new Question("Which planet is known as the Red Planet?", 
                new string[] { "Mars", "Venus", "Jupiter", "Saturn" }, 'A'),
            new Question("What is the largest mammal?", 
                new string[] { "Elephant", "Blue Whale", "Giraffe", "Hippopotamus" }, 'B'),
            // Add more questions as needed
        };

        Quiz quiz = new Quiz(questions);
        quiz.Run();
    }
}
```

### Step 6: Running the Game

Build and run your project. You should see the trivia quiz running in the console, asking questions one by one, accepting your answers, and finally showing your score.

### Step 7: Enhancing the Game

To make the game more interesting, consider adding:

- Timed questions.
- Different difficulty levels.
- More categories of questions.
- A leaderboard to save high scores.
- Random question ordering.

### Conclusion

You've now created a basic console-based trivia quiz game in C#. This project not only helps you understand fundamental programming concepts but also provides a fun way to engage with users. Keep experimenting and adding features to make it even better!
